import json

outpath = "competitions/agent-shield/data/knowledge/regulatory.jsonl"
lines = []

def a(cat, title, text):
    lines.append(json.dumps({"category": cat, "title": title, "text": text}, ensure_ascii=False))

# === HIPAA (30 chunks) ===
a("HIPAA","HIPAA Overview and Scope","The Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act (HIPAA) of 1996 establishes national standards for protecting sensitive patient health information. HIPAA applies to covered entities (health plans, healthcare clearinghouses, and healthcare providers who transmit health information electronically) and their business associates. The Act comprises the Privacy Rule (45 CFR Part 160 and Subparts A and E of Part 164), the Security Rule (Subparts A and C of Part 164), the Breach Notification Rule (Subpart D of Part 164), and the Enforcement Rule. Violations can result in civil monetary penalties ranging from $100 to $50,000 per violation, with annual maximums of $1.5 million per violation category, and criminal penalties including fines up to $250,000 and imprisonment up to 10 years.")
a("HIPAA","Protected Health Information Definition","Protected Health Information (PHI) under HIPAA is any individually identifiable health information held or transmitted by a covered entity or its business associate, in any form or medium. PHI includes information relating to past, present, or future physical or mental health condition, provision of healthcare, or payment for healthcare, that identifies or could reasonably identify the individual. PHI encompasses medical records, lab results, billing information, and health information combined with demographic data. PHI applies to all forms: electronic (ePHI), paper, and oral. De-identified health information meeting Privacy Rule standards is not PHI and is not subject to HIPAA restrictions.")
a("HIPAA","The 18 HIPAA Identifiers","HIPAA Safe Harbor de-identification requires removal of 18 identifiers: (1) Names, (2) Geographic data smaller than a state, (3) All dates except year including birth, admission, discharge, death, and ages over 89, (4) Telephone numbers, (5) Fax numbers, (6) Email addresses, (7) Social Security numbers, (8) Medical record numbers, (9) Health plan beneficiary numbers, (10) Account numbers, (11) Certificate/license numbers, (12) Vehicle identifiers including license plates, (13) Device identifiers, (14) Web URLs, (15) IP addresses, (16) Biometric identifiers, (17) Full-face photographs, (18) Any other unique identifying number or code. The entity must have no actual knowledge that remaining information could identify an individual.")
a("HIPAA","Section 164.502 Permitted Uses and Disclosures","Under 45 CFR 164.502, a covered entity may use or disclose PHI only as permitted or required by the Privacy Rule. Permitted uses include: to the individual; for treatment, payment, and healthcare operations (TPO); incident to permitted use; pursuant to valid authorization under 164.508; for facility directories and notifications under 164.510; and for public interest activities under 164.512. The minimum necessary standard applies to most disclosures, requiring only the minimum PHI necessary for the intended purpose.")
a("HIPAA","Treatment Payment and Healthcare Operations","HIPAA permits PHI use and disclosure without authorization for TPO. Treatment includes provision, coordination, and management of healthcare including provider consultations and referrals. Payment encompasses premium collection, coverage determination, benefit provision, reimbursement, and utilization review. Healthcare Operations include quality assessment, competency assurance, medical review, legal and auditing services, business planning, and grievance resolution. The minimum necessary standard applies to payment and operations but not treatment-related disclosures between providers.")
a("HIPAA","Section 164.508 Authorization Requirements","Section 164.508 specifies when valid authorization is required for PHI disclosures not otherwise permitted, including marketing, PHI sale, and psychotherapy notes. Valid authorizations must contain: PHI description, authorized discloser and recipient, expiration date or event, purpose, and individual signature and date. Required statements cover: right to revoke, whether treatment is conditioned on authorization, and re-disclosure potential. Authorization must be in plain language. Compound authorizations are generally prohibited except in limited research contexts.")
a("HIPAA","Section 164.512 Law Enforcement Disclosures","Under 164.512(f), covered entities may disclose PHI to law enforcement without authorization for: court orders, warrants, subpoenas, or qualifying administrative requests; identifying suspects, fugitives, witnesses, or missing persons (limited to name, address, DOB, SSN, blood type, injury type, treatment date/time, and physical characteristics); crime victim information with agreement or immediate enforcement need; suspected criminal death; evidence of on-premises crime; and medical emergency crime reporting. These do not permit blanket sharing of records with police.")
a("HIPAA","Section 164.524 Patient Right of Access","Under 164.524, individuals may inspect and obtain PHI copies in designated record sets. Entities must act within 30 days (extendable by 30). Electronic information must be available electronically. Fees limited to reasonable copying, postage, and summary costs. Access may be denied for psychotherapy notes, legal proceeding compilations, or certain research records. Reviewable denials include endangerment situations. Denied individuals may request review by a designated licensed healthcare professional.")
a("HIPAA","Minimum Necessary Standard","The minimum necessary standard under 164.502(b) requires reasonable efforts to limit PHI to what is needed. Entities must implement policies limiting access by job role and define appropriate access conditions. Applies to payment, operations, and public interest disclosures. Does NOT apply to: treatment disclosures between providers, disclosures to the individual, authorized disclosures, HHS compliance investigations, legally required disclosures, or HIPAA compliance disclosures.")
a("HIPAA","Business Associate Agreements","BAAs are required between covered entities and business associates (billing companies, cloud providers, EHR vendors, attorneys, accountants, IT contractors). BAAs must: establish permitted PHI uses, require safeguards, require breach reporting, ensure subcontractor restrictions, make PHI available for individual rights, provide HHS audit access, and require PHI return or destruction at termination. Entities knowing of material breaches must cure or terminate the contract.")
a("HIPAA","Breach Notification Rule","The Breach Notification Rule (45 CFR 164.400-414) requires notification after unauthorized acquisition, access, use, or disclosure of unsecured PHI compromising security or privacy. Individual notification within 60 days of discovery. Must include: breach description, information types, protective steps, investigation efforts, and contact procedures. Breaches affecting 500+ in a state require media notification. All 500+ breaches reported to HHS immediately; under 500 annually.")
a("HIPAA","60-Day Breach Timeline","The 60-day clock starts on discovery date, not when the breach occurred. Discovery is when the breach is known or should reasonably have been known by any employee, officer, or agent. Business associates must notify the entity, starting the 60-day clock for individual notification. Missing the deadline is a separate violation. State laws may impose shorter deadlines that must also be met.")
a("HIPAA","De-identification Safe Harbor","Safe Harbor under 164.514(b)(2) requires removing all 18 identifier categories plus having no actual knowledge that remaining info could identify anyone. When met, data is de-identified and exempt from HIPAA. Straightforward but reduces utility: geography generalized to three-digit zips (000 for populations under 20,000), all dates except year removed.")
a("HIPAA","De-identification Expert Determination","Expert Determination under 164.514(b)(1) allows a qualified expert to certify very small re-identification risk using accepted statistical methods. The expert documents methods and results, considering data recipients, complementary sources, and available re-identification techniques. Preserves more utility than Safe Harbor by allowing retention of identifiers when risk remains very small. Preferred for research requiring granular data.")
a("HIPAA","Patient Rights Amendment of Records","Under 164.526, individuals may request PHI amendment within designated record sets. Entity acts within 60 days (extendable by 30). May deny if: PHI not created by entity, not in designated record set, not accessible under 164.524, or accurate and complete. Denials require written explanation, disagreement rights, and complaint information. All documents appended to the record. Accepted amendments require informing relevant parties.")
a("HIPAA","Patient Rights Accounting of Disclosures","Under 164.528, individuals receive accounting of PHI disclosures made in the prior six years, including date, recipient, information description, and purpose. Exempt: TPO, individual disclosures, incident disclosures, authorized disclosures, facility directories, care-involved persons, national security, and correctional institutions. Entity acts within 60 days (extendable by 30). First annual accounting is free.")
a("HIPAA","Security Rule Administrative Safeguards","Under 164.308: security management (risk analysis, management, sanctions, activity review), assigned security responsibility, workforce security (authorization, supervision, clearance, termination), information access management, security training (reminders, malware protection, login monitoring, passwords), incident procedures, contingency planning (backup, recovery, emergency mode, testing, criticality analysis), evaluation, and BA contracts.")
a("HIPAA","Security Rule Technical Safeguards","Under 164.312: access control (unique IDs, emergency access, auto-logoff, encryption), audit controls, integrity controls, person/entity authentication, and transmission security (integrity and encryption). Required specs: unique IDs, audit controls, authentication. Addressable specs: auto-logoff, encryption at rest, integrity mechanisms, transmission encryption. Addressable means implement if reasonable or document alternatives.")
a("HIPAA","Psychotherapy Notes Protections","Psychotherapy notes (164.501) are mental health professional counseling session notes separated from the medical record. Exclude: prescriptions, session times, treatment modalities, clinical tests, and diagnosis/status/plan/symptom/progress summaries. Require specific authorization separate from general authorizations. Exceptions: originator treatment use, entity training, legal requirements, HHS investigations, serious threat aversion, and deceased patient activities.")
a("HIPAA","HIPAA and Research","PHI may be used in research with: individual authorization, IRB or Privacy Board waiver (minimal risk, impracticable without waiver, adequate identifier protection plan), preparatory activities (PHI stays within entity), and decedent research. Limited data sets allowed under data use agreements. De-identified data is not subject to HIPAA and can be freely used for research.")
a("HIPAA","HIPAA Enforcement and Penalties","OCR enforces HIPAA with four tiers: Tier 1 (unknowing) $100-$50,000; Tier 2 (reasonable cause) $1,000-$50,000; Tier 3 (willful neglect, corrected in 30 days) $10,000-$50,000; Tier 4 (willful neglect, uncorrected) $50,000. Annual caps $1.5 million. Criminal: $50,000/1 year for knowing; $100,000/5 years for false pretenses; $250,000/10 years for commercial/malicious intent. State AGs may bring civil actions.")
a("HIPAA","Substance Abuse Records 42 CFR Part 2","SUD treatment records receive additional protection under Part 2 for federally assisted programs. More restrictive than HIPAA: consent required for nearly all disclosures, must specify recipient and purpose, re-disclosure prohibited without consent, records cannot be used criminally against patients. 2020 CARES Act aligned some provisions allowing TPO with written consent, but law enforcement still requires court order. The more protective regulation governs.")
a("HIPAA","Right to Request Restrictions","Under 164.522, individuals may request PHI use restrictions for TPO and care-involved persons. Entities generally need not agree but must restrict health plan disclosures for services paid fully out of pocket. Agreed restrictions apply except in emergencies. Restrictions remain until patient revocation, mutual termination, or entity prospective termination notice.")
a("HIPAA","HIPAA and Minors","HIPAA defers to state law for minors. Parents are typically personal representatives but not when: state law allows minor consent and the minor consented, a court authorized treatment, or parent agreed to provider-minor confidentiality. In abuse/endangerment, entities may decline parent representative status. Professional judgment applies when state law is silent. Organizations must track state minor consent laws.")
a("HIPAA","HIPAA and Cloud Computing","Cloud service providers handling ePHI are business associates requiring BAAs regardless of access level. Even encrypted storage qualifies. Must implement Security Rule safeguards: encryption at rest and transit, access controls, audit logging, backup, disaster recovery, breach notification, data location restrictions, multi-tenancy isolation, secure termination disposal. Entity and CSP share risk assessment responsibility.")
a("HIPAA","HIPAA Preemption and State Law","HIPAA is a federal floor; more stringent state laws are not preempted. Under 160.203, HIPAA preempts contrary state law unless it provides greater protection, relates to disease/injury reporting, child abuse, public health, or the Secretary grants exception. Analysis is provision-by-provision. California CMIA provides broader protections. Various states enhance mental health, HIV/AIDS, and genetic protections. Multi-state organizations comply with most protective standard.")
a("HIPAA","HIPAA and Telehealth","Telehealth must comply with Privacy and Security Rules: HIPAA-compliant encrypted platforms, vendor BAAs, end-to-end video encryption, patient identity verification, private locations, state-required consent, platform access controls, session logs, telehealth privacy training. Social media livestreaming is never HIPAA-compliant for telehealth.")
a("HIPAA","HIPAA and Social Media","Social media violations: posting patient photos/info, discussing identifiable cases without names, sharing workplace images capturing PHI, responding to reviews with treatment info, livestreaming clinical settings. Policies must prohibit unauthorized sharing, define identifiable info, restrict clinical photography, address personal devices, establish consequences. Even well-intentioned posts can violate HIPAA.")
a("HIPAA","HIPAA and Genetic Information","Genetic info receives enhanced protection under HIPAA and GINA. Genetic info is PHI when held by covered entities. Privacy Rule prohibits health plans from using it for underwriting. GINA Title I prohibits insurer use for enrollment/coverage; Title II prohibits employment discrimination. Includes: individual and family genetic tests, family medical history, genetic service requests, and fetal/embryo genetic info.")
a("HIPAA","Facility Directory and Disaster Exceptions","Under 164.510(a), directories may include patient name, location, general condition, and religious affiliation, disclosed to clergy or persons asking by name. Patients must be informed and can restrict. In emergencies, disclosure if consistent with prior preferences. Under 164.510(b), PHI for disaster relief without authorization when in patient best interest. Public health emergencies may trigger additional flexibilities.")

# === GDPR (30 chunks) ===
a("GDPR","GDPR Overview and Scope","The General Data Protection Regulation (EU 2016/679) took effect May 25, 2018, applying to all organizations processing personal data of EEA individuals regardless of location. Under Article 3, it covers EU-established organizations and those outside the EU offering goods/services to or monitoring behavior of EU individuals. Fines: up to 20 million euros or 4% of global turnover for serious violations, 10 million euros or 2% for less severe. Replaced the 1995 Data Protection Directive.")
a("GDPR","Article 6 Lawful Bases","Six lawful bases: (a) Consent; (b) Contract performance; (c) Legal obligation; (d) Vital interests; (e) Public task; (f) Legitimate interests unless overridden by data subject interests. Must determine and document basis before processing. Cannot change retroactively. Each basis carries different obligations.")
a("GDPR","Article 9 Special Categories","Prohibits processing special categories unless exceptions apply: racial/ethnic origin, political opinions, religious/philosophical beliefs, trade union membership, genetic data, biometric identification data, health data, sex life/orientation data. Exceptions: explicit consent, employment law, vital interests, not-for-profit, manifestly public data, legal claims, public interest, healthcare, public health, archiving/research. Additional safeguards required.")
a("GDPR","Article 17 Right to Erasure","Erasure without undue delay when: data unnecessary, consent withdrawn without other basis, subject objects without overriding grounds, unlawful processing, legal requirement, children information society data. Exceptions: expression freedom, legal obligation, public health, archiving/research if erasure impairs objectives, legal claims. When data was public, controller must inform other controllers.")
a("GDPR","GDPR Consent Requirements","Must be freely given (no bundling, no power imbalance, granular), specific (particular purpose), informed (controller identity, data, purposes, withdrawal right), unambiguous (affirmative action, not silence or pre-ticked). Withdrawal as easy as giving. Controller must demonstrate consent. Distinguishable requests in plain language. Children need parental authorization. Not free in power imbalances.")
a("GDPR","Article 15 Right of Access","Subjects may confirm processing and access data with: purposes, categories, recipients, retention period, rights info, complaint right, source info, automated decision-making, transfer safeguards. Free copy (reasonable fee for extras). One-month response (extendable by two). Identity verification without excessive burden.")
a("GDPR","Rights Rectification and Portability","Article 16: correct inaccurate data, complete incomplete data. Article 20: receive data in structured, machine-readable format, transmit to other controllers. Portability only for consent/contract-based automated processing. Direct controller-to-controller where feasible. Covers provided data only, not inferred/derived.")
a("GDPR","Rights Objection and Restriction","Article 21: object to public interest or legitimate interests processing. Controller ceases unless compelling overriding grounds or legal claims. Direct marketing objection is absolute. Article 18: restriction when accuracy contested, unlawful but erasure opposed, controller no longer needs but subject does for claims, objection pending verification. Restricted data: stored only, processed with consent/claims/rights/public interest.")
a("GDPR","Article 32 Security of Processing","Appropriate technical and organizational measures considering: state of art, costs, processing context, risk. Specifically: pseudonymization and encryption, ongoing confidentiality/integrity/availability/resilience, timely incident restoration, regular effectiveness testing. Authorized persons process only on controller instructions.")
a("GDPR","Article 33 Breach Notification 72h","Notify supervisory authority without undue delay, within 72 hours. Late notifications require delay reasons. Describe: breach nature with numbers, DPO contact, likely consequences, measures taken. Not required if unlikely to risk rights. Article 34: high-risk communication to subjects unless encrypted, risk mitigated, or individual notice disproportionate.")
a("GDPR","Data Protection Impact Assessment","Required when processing likely results in high risk. Specifically: systematic extensive automated evaluation, large-scale special/criminal data, large-scale systematic public monitoring. Must contain: processing description, necessity/proportionality assessment, risk assessment, planned safeguards. Unmitigatable high risk requires Article 36 prior consultation.")
a("GDPR","Cross-Border Transfers","Articles 44-49 restrict EEA transfers. Bases: adequacy decisions for adequate-protection countries; safeguards including SCCs, BCRs, codes, certifications; and derogations including explicit consent, contract necessity, public interest, claims, vital interests. Schrems II invalidated Privacy Shield, requires supplementary measures. Transfer Impact Assessments evaluate recipient protections. EU-US Data Privacy Framework (July 2023) for certified US companies.")
a("GDPR","Standard Contractual Clauses","Commission-approved transfer terms. June 2021 modular: C2C, C2P, P2P, P2C. Obligations: importer security, government disclosure notification, subject request assistance, exporter Transfer Impact Assessment, processing documentation. Non-compliance notification allows transfer suspension. Core clauses unmodifiable; supplementary non-contradicting clauses allowed.")
a("GDPR","Controller vs Processor","Controllers determine purposes/means, bear primary compliance: lawful bases, design/default, records, DPIAs, DPO, subject requests. Processors: follow instructions, confidentiality, security, sub-processors with authorization, assist requests/DPIAs, notify breaches, delete/return data. Article 28 contract required specifying subject matter, duration, nature, purpose, data types, subject categories.")
a("GDPR","Article 8 Children Data","Information society services: consent valid at 16+. Below 16, parental consent required. States may lower to 13 minimum. Reasonable verification efforts required. Clear child-accessible information. Erasure right reinforced for childhood data.")
a("GDPR","Data Protection by Design and Default","Article 25: by design means appropriate measures at design and processing time (pseudonymization). By default: only necessary data collected, limited processing, minimized storage, restricted accessibility. Consider state of art, cost, context, risks. Certification may demonstrate compliance. Embed from earliest design.")
a("GDPR","Data Protection Officer","Required for: public authorities, core large-scale systematic monitoring, core large-scale special/criminal data. Expert knowledge, necessary resources, no task instructions, no performance penalties, highest management reporting. Tasks: advising, compliance monitoring, DPIA advice, authority cooperation, contact point. May be staff/external, serve multiple conflict-free organizations.")
a("GDPR","Records of Processing Activities","Article 30: controllers record details, purposes, categories, recipients, transfers, erasure limits, security. Processors record details, categories per controller, transfers, security. Written (including electronic), available to authorities. Sub-250 organizations exempt unless risky, non-occasional, or special category processing.")
a("GDPR","Binding Corporate Rules","Internal multinational policies for intra-group transfers under Article 47. Include: structure, transfers, binding nature, principles, rights, liability, information, complaints, verification, change reporting, authority cooperation. Comprehensive but 12-24 months for approval.")
a("GDPR","Automated Decision-Making","Article 22: right against solely automated decisions with legal/significant effects. Exceptions: contract necessity, law with safeguards, explicit consent. Safeguards: human intervention, expressing views, contesting decisions. Special category profiling: explicit consent or substantial public interest. Meaningful information about logic, significance, consequences required.")
a("GDPR","Legitimate Interest Assessment","Three-part: purpose test (real, present interest), necessity test (less intrusive alternatives?), balancing test (controller vs subject interests considering data nature, expectations, impact, safeguards). Must document. Cannot use for: withdrawn consent without basis, children, public authority tasks.")
a("GDPR","GDPR Enforcement Precedents","Amazon 746M euros (consent); Meta/WhatsApp 225M (transparency); Meta/Instagram 405M (children); Clearview AI 60M+ (biometrics); British Airways 20M pounds (security); H&M 35M (surveillance); Google 150M (cookie rejection). Focus: consent, transparency, minimization, security, children, substantive compliance.")
a("GDPR","GDPR Core Principles","Article 5: (1a) lawfulness, fairness, transparency; (1b) purpose limitation for specified, explicit, legitimate purposes; (1c) data minimization, adequate, relevant, limited; (1d) accuracy, kept up to date; (1e) storage limitation, identifiable form only as necessary; (1f) integrity and confidentiality; (2) accountability, controller must demonstrate compliance.")
a("GDPR","GDPR Accountability Principle","Article 5(2): controller responsible for and must demonstrate compliance with all principles. Requires proactive measures: documentation, policies, procedures, reviews, audits, staff training, DPO where required, design/default implementation, processing records. Shifts burden from rule-following to actively demonstrating ongoing compliance.")
a("GDPR","GDPR Territorial Scope","Article 3: establishment in EU (regardless of processing location), offering goods/services to EU individuals (EU languages, currencies, EU customer references), monitoring EU individual behavior. Non-EU controllers must designate Article 27 representatives in affected Member States. Broad scope prevents geographic GDPR evasion.")
a("GDPR","GDPR Direct Marketing","Consent and legitimate interests most common bases. Article 21 direct marketing objection is absolute, must be noted at first communication. ePrivacy Directive requires opt-in for electronic marketing with limited existing customer exceptions. Clear free opt-out always required. Marketing profiling subject to same objection. Processing ceases immediately upon objection.")
a("GDPR","GDPR International Cooperation","Consistency mechanism (Articles 63-67) ensures uniform application. Lead authority by main establishment. One-stop-shop for cross-border organizations. EDPB issues opinions, guidelines, binding dispute decisions. Mutual assistance for information sharing. Joint operations for cross-state investigations. Prevents regulatory arbitrage.")
a("GDPR","GDPR Right to Complaint and Remedies","Article 77: complain to supervisory authority (informed within three months). Article 78: judicial remedy against authority. Article 79: judicial remedy against controller/processor. Article 80: not-for-profit representation. Article 82: compensation for material or non-material damage. Controllers liable for infringing processing; processors for processor-specific failures. Joint parties liable for entire damage.")
a("GDPR","GDPR Purpose Limitation and Minimization","Article 5(1)(b): collected for specified, explicit, legitimate purposes, not processed incompatibly. Archiving, scientific, historical, statistical purposes considered compatible. Article 5(1)(c): adequate, relevant, limited to what is necessary. Controllers should regularly review collection practices and eliminate unnecessary data elements.")
a("GDPR","GDPR Data Retention and Accuracy","Article 5(1)(d): data must be accurate, kept up to date, inaccurate data erased or rectified without delay. Article 5(1)(e): kept in identifiable form only as long as necessary. Longer for archiving, research, statistics with safeguards. Controllers should establish documented retention schedules and systematic deletion processes.")

# === KYC/AML (20 chunks) ===
a("KYC_AML","Customer Due Diligence Overview","CDD requires: customer identification and verification (name, DOB, address, ID from reliable sources), beneficial ownership identification (25%+ equity owners), understanding relationship nature and purpose (expected activity for risk profiles), and ongoing monitoring (suspicious transactions, information updates). Performed at: relationship establishment, occasional above-threshold transactions, suspected laundering/terrorism, and when doubting prior identification.")
a("KYC_AML","Enhanced Due Diligence","EDD for higher-risk: high-risk FATF jurisdictions, PEPs, complex transactions, correspondent banking, private banking, non-face-to-face. Measures: additional ID, additional verification sources, senior management approval, enhanced monitoring, source of wealth/funds, transaction rationale, regulated first payment, enhanced scrutiny. Documentation maintained for regulators.")
a("KYC_AML","Suspicious Activity Reports","Filed with FinCEN for suspected violations, laundering, or BSA violations. Deadline: 30 days (60 if no suspect). Reportable: $5,000+ suspected illegal funds, BSA evasion, no lawful purpose, or facilitating crime. Tipping off is federal offense. Retained five years. Supporting docs maintained. Account monitoring continues. Good-faith safe harbor.")
a("KYC_AML","Politically Exposed Persons","PEPs: heads of state, senior officials, state enterprise executives, party officials, military officers, central bank members. Extends to family and close associates. Elevated corruption risk. Required: risk-based determination, senior management approval, source of wealth/funds, enhanced monitoring. Screen at onboarding and periodically using reliable databases.")
a("KYC_AML","Bank Secrecy Act Requirements","BSA (31 USC 5311-5330): CTRs for cash over $10,000; SARs for suspicious $5,000+; CIP for identity; beneficial ownership for entities; recordkeeping for $3,000+ transfers; AML program with controls, officer, training, testing. Willful violations: civil up to $500,000; criminal $250,000 and five years, ten years for patterns.")
a("KYC_AML","Customer Identification Program","Under 31 CFR 1020.220: verify identity at account opening. Minimum: name, DOB, address, ID number. Risk-based verification: documentary (government photo ID), non-documentary (agencies, references), or both. Procedures for: unverifiable identities, terrorist list comparison, verification notice. Records five years after closure.")
a("KYC_AML","Beneficial Ownership Requirements","Under 31 CFR 1010.230: identify 25%+ equity owners and one management-responsible individual at opening. Exempt: banks, broker-dealers, insurers, public companies, governments, investment companies, US entities. Same CIP information required. Records five years, updated on risk triggers.")
a("KYC_AML","AML Transaction Monitoring","Combines automated rules with risk analysis. Red flags: structuring below thresholds, rapid layering, profile inconsistency, high-risk jurisdictions, round/near-threshold amounts, frequent exchanges, multi-account coordination, shell company wires, unusual cash deposits. Programs need: calibrated scenarios, tuning, 30-60 day investigations, escalation, documentation, SAR filing.")
a("KYC_AML","Money Laundering Stages","Three stages: placement (introducing illicit funds), layering (complex transaction layers), integration (legitimate reintroduction). Typologies: trade-based invoice manipulation, real estate via shells, nominees, funnel accounts, crypto mixing, professional networks, cash business commingling. FATF and FinCEN provide updates.")
a("KYC_AML","Sanctions Screening and OFAC","Screen OFAC lists: SDN, SSI, FSE, Non-SDN Menu-Based. At: onboarding, info changes, transactions, list updates. Handle variations, transliterations, aliases. True matches: block/reject, report within 10 days. Programs: management commitment, risk assessment, controls, testing, training. Civil: $330,000 or 2x value; criminal: $1M and 20 years.")
a("KYC_AML","Shell Companies and Correspondent Banking","Shells (no assets/operations) obscure ownership and layer transactions. Red flags: secrecy jurisdictions, nominees, no presence, complex ownership, inconsistent transactions. Correspondent risks: nested banking, payable-through, high-risk clearing. Mitigation: understand respondent AML, assess jurisdiction, monitor, review periodically, contract provisions.")
a("KYC_AML","Cryptocurrency AML","FinCEN classifies crypto businesses as MSBs. Obligations: registration, AML program, CTRs, SARs, travel rule, CDD. Challenges: pseudonymity, mixers, privacy coins, P2P, DeFi, cross-border, evolution. Blockchain analytics trace transactions and identify high-risk addresses. FATF Travel Rule requires originator/beneficiary information.")
a("KYC_AML","Trade-Based Money Laundering","Exploits trade complexity. Techniques: over/under-invoicing, multiple invoicing, false descriptions, phantom shipments. Red flags: value discrepancies, inconsistent patterns, unrelated-country payments, complex routes, off-market pricing, free trade zones. Detection: AML-trade finance collaboration, pricing databases, normal pattern analysis.")
a("KYC_AML","FinCEN Regulatory Examination","Delegated to OCC, Fed, FDIC, NCUA, SEC. Assesses: controls, monitoring, CDD/beneficial ownership, CTR compliance, training, audit independence, board oversight. Deficiencies: MRAs, MRIAs, enforcement, cease/desist, penalties. Maintain ready documentation, self-assess, remediate, document. Focus: digital assets, beneficial ownership, TBML, proliferation.")
a("KYC_AML","AML Whistleblower Protections","AML Whistleblower Improvement Act (2020): 10-30% of sanctions over $1M. BSA anti-retaliation: no discharge, demotion, threats; reinstatement and back pay; identity confidentiality. Institutions: maintain channels, ensure compliance board access, prohibit retaliation, train rights, investigate thoroughly.")
a("KYC_AML","Customer Risk Rating","Institutions assign ratings based on: geographic risk, product risk, customer type risk, and transaction behavior risk. High-risk gets EDD and frequent reviews. Ratings must be documented, periodically reassessed, and updated. Effective models are calibrated with historical data and validated regularly.")
a("KYC_AML","Currency Transaction Reports","CTRs filed for cash over $10,000 in a business day on FinCEN Form 112 within 15 days. Include: transactor identity, behalf identity, transaction description, institution info. Structuring to avoid CTRs is a federal crime even with legitimate funds. Staff trained to identify structuring and file SARs.")
a("KYC_AML","AML Program Five Pillars","Five pillars: (1) internal policies, procedures, controls; (2) qualified BSA compliance officer with authority and resources; (3) ongoing training on BSA/AML, policies, and new typologies; (4) independent testing by qualified auditors at risk-based intervals; (5) risk-based ongoing CDD including beneficial ownership. Tailored to institution size, complexity, products, customers, geography.")
a("KYC_AML","FATF International Standards","FATF sets AML/CFT standards through 40 Recommendations covering: criminalization, preventive measures, transparency, competent authorities, and international cooperation. Conducts mutual evaluations, publishes high-risk and non-cooperative jurisdiction lists, issues risk guidance. Grey-listed countries under increased monitoring; blacklisted face counter-measures. Institutions incorporate FATF into risk-based approach.")
a("KYC_AML","Correspondent Banking Due Diligence","Beyond standard CDD: understand respondent business/reputation/AML controls, check enforcement history, assess home country framework, assess nested relationships, obtain senior management approval. Enhanced diligence for high-risk jurisdictions. Periodic documented review. Shell banks (no physical presence) must never receive correspondent services.")

# === Social Engineering (20 chunks) ===
a("social_engineering","Authority Impersonation","Attackers impersonate compliance officers, auditors, regulators, referencing real frameworks and deadlines. Red flags: unsolicited data requests, bypass pressure, unfamiliar contacts, no callback info. Defenses: independently verify through official channels, never provide credentials on inbound requests, escalate to supervisor and actual compliance, document, follow verification regardless of claimed authority.")
a("social_engineering","Urgency Manipulation","Forces bypassing security through time pressure: audit tomorrow, breach in progress, CEO needs data now, emergency review. Triggers fight-or-flight reducing critical thinking. Red flags: artificial deadlines, circumvention requests, emotional pressure, importance-inconsistent channels. Defenses: pause, verify independently, consult supervisor, document. No legitimate authority demands bypassing security for urgency.")
a("social_engineering","Pretexting for Data Access","Fabricates scenarios for unauthorized access. Healthcare: new employee, partner organization, vendor, journalist. Finance: client attorney, surprise examiner, corporate investigation. Defenses: verify through established channels, maintain strict access control, train on patterns, callback verification, written authorization, encourage questioning.")
a("social_engineering","Insider Threat Indicators","Behavioral: irrelevant record access, unusual hours/locations, disgruntlement, unexplained finances, policy violations, out-of-scope interest, unauthorized copying, unjustified access requests. Technical: unusual queries, unauthorized media, security circumvention, post-notice access, external transfers. Responses: least-privilege, audit logs, access reviews, anonymous reporting, anomaly monitoring, timely revocation.")
a("social_engineering","Proper Verification Procedures","Essential: callback using independently obtained numbers, multi-factor identity verification, role-based authorization confirmation, written requests with audit trails, supervisor approval for unusual requests, out-of-band confirmation through different channels. Document procedures, train staff, simulate regularly, build verification-valuing culture.")
a("social_engineering","Phishing in Regulated Industries","From apparent EHR vendors, insurers, regulators, banks. Spear phishing uses social media intel. Characteristics: spoofed domains, urgent compliance actions, credential harvesting, malware as regulatory docs, internal project references. Defenses: SPF/DKIM/DMARC, URL filtering, sandboxing, simulation training, reporting, verification protocols, incident response.")
a("social_engineering","Tailgating Physical Access","Unauthorized facility entry via courtesy. Tactics: carrying items, authoritative uniforms, group timing, conversation distraction. Reaches PHI, records, systems. Defenses: training, mantraps, visitor management, escort requirements, cameras, challenge culture, consistent enforcement, penetration testing.")
a("social_engineering","Baiting and Quid Pro Quo","Baiting: malware-infected media with enticing labels. Quid pro quo: offering value for credentials/access. Defenses: disable auto-run, USB controls, never insert unknown devices, reject unsolicited assistance, easy reporting channels.")
a("social_engineering","Vishing in Healthcare","Voice phishing targets front desk, nurses, records, billing. Scenarios: forgotten record number, faxed records to unverified number, insurance details, IT credentials, public health data. Defenses: specific identifying info required, callback to file numbers, scenario training, phone PHI protocols, logging, limited telephone disclosure.")
a("social_engineering","Social Media OSINT","Harvested: names/titles from LinkedIn, interests from social platforms, conference attendance, announcements, tech from job postings. Enables: personalized phishing, impersonation, project referencing, trust exploitation, transition timing. Defenses: social media policies, OSINT monitoring, oversharing training, limited public org charts, exposure assessments.")
a("social_engineering","Business Email Compromise","Targets: finance (wires), HR (W-2s), IT (access), compliance (fake regulatory), executives (legal demands). Dual risk: financial and regulatory. Indicators: address variations, unusual patterns, payment changes, secrecy, approval bypasses. Defenses: multi-person authorization, out-of-band verification, email auth, skepticism training, dual-track response.")
a("social_engineering","Deepfakes and AI Social Engineering","AI enables: synthetic voice, fabricated video, LLM phishing, automated scaling. Impacts: deepfake executive authorization, synthetic identity bypass, contextual phishing, mass vishing. Defenses: multi-factor out-of-band verification, code words, behavioral analysis, voice replication awareness, real-time fabrication training, AI scenario testing.")
a("social_engineering","Supply Chain Social Engineering","Through third parties: vendor impersonation, partner compromise, trust exploitation, BA targeting, compromised vendor email. Healthcare: EHR/device/insurer. Finance: payment/tech vendors. Defenses: current vendor contacts, strict controls, MFA, access monitoring, vendor assessments, protocols, privilege reviews.")
a("social_engineering","Reverse Social Engineering","Attacker becomes resource targets seek. Phases: sabotage, advertising contact, assisting while extracting/installing. Fake helpdesks, official problem notices, compromised support, fake websites. Target-initiated contact creates trust. Defenses: current contacts, verified channels, monitor suspicious communications.")
a("social_engineering","Data Disposal and Dumpster Diving","Improper disposal is a major vector. HIPAA requires disposal policies; FTC Disposal Rule covers consumer reports. Methods: cross-cut shredding, degaussing, cryptographic erasure, certified destruction, secure bins. Audit practices, training, clean desk policies.")
a("social_engineering","Security Awareness Training","Build culture: regular simulations, immediate feedback, clear metrics, role-tailored content, industry examples, non-punitive reporting, recognition, incident response integration, leadership modeling, tabletop exercises, emerging technique updates, onboarding integration. Goal: verification as professional diligence.")
a("social_engineering","Financial Pretext Calling","Pretexts: lost checkbook, correspondent bank, law enforcement, client attorney, other branch. GLBA prohibits financial pretexting. Defenses: callback to known numbers, MFA for phone, strict disclosure limits, written authorization, scenario training, documenting inquiries.")
a("social_engineering","Watering Hole Attacks","Compromise industry-frequented sites: associations, education, regulatory portals, news, vendor forums. Exploit familiar-site trust, bypass unknown-domain controls. Defenses: updated browsers, web filtering, browser isolation, traffic monitoring, segmentation, endpoint detection.")
a("social_engineering","Credential Harvesting Techniques","Replicate legitimate login portals for EHR, banking, insurance, compliance systems. Techniques: look-alike domains, HTTPS certificates, exact visual replication, real-time credential relay, compromised redirect hosts. MFA reduces effectiveness but relay attacks exist. Implement phishing-resistant FIDO2 hardware keys.")
a("social_engineering","Social Engineering Regulatory Reporting","Victims face dual obligations: incident response and regulatory reporting. HIPAA: unauthorized PHI disclosure requires 60-day breach notification. GDPR: unauthorized access reported to authority within 72 hours. BSA/AML: unauthorized access or fraud requires SAR. GLBA: report to primary regulator. Incident plans must address both remediation and notification timelines.")

